2. What is the OSI Model?

The Open Systems Interconnection (OSI) Model is a conceptual framework that divides network communication into seven layers. 
Each layer performs a specific function and communicates with the layers directly above and below it.


OSI MODEL Diagram 

+----------------------+
| 7. Application       |
+----------------------+
| 6. Presentation      |
+----------------------+
| 5. Session           |
+----------------------+
| 4. Transport         |
+----------------------+
| 3. Network           |
+----------------------+
| 2. Data Link         |
+----------------------+
| 1. Physical          |
+----------------------+


| Layer | Name         | Main Function            | Example Protocols      |
| ----- | ------------ | ------------------------ | ---------------------- |
| 7     | Application  | User services            | HTTP, HTTPS, FTP, SMTP |
| 6     | Presentation | Encryption & Compression | SSL/TLS                |
| 5     | Session      | Session management       | NetBIOS                |
| 4     | Transport    | Reliable communication   | TCP, UDP               |
| 3     | Network      | Routing                  | IP, ICMP               |
| 2     | Data Link    | MAC addressing           | Ethernet               |
| 1     | Physical     | Signal transmission      | Cables, Fiber          |



| Layer       | Device       |
| ----------- | ------------ |
| Physical    | Hub          |
| Data Link   | Switch       |
| Network     | Router       |
| Application | Proxy Server |


Application Layer → Sends an HTTP request.
Presentation Layer → Encrypts the data using TLS.
Session Layer → Maintains the communication session.
Transport Layer → Breaks data into TCP segments.
Network Layer → Routes packets using IP.
Data Link Layer → Adds MAC addresses.
Physical Layer → Sends bits through Ethernet or Wi-Fi.


